{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 986 (PR #3588) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/3588.","id":"vf_3eed65065981d7f6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Full solution.","id":"vf_904789e6943e45f9","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #986: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. For any fixed $k\\geq 3$,\\[R(k,n) \\gg \\frac{n^{k-1}}{(\\log n)^c}\\]for some constant $c=c(k)>0$. Current best: The best general bounds available are\\[\\frac{n^{\\frac{k+1}{2}}}{(\\log n)^{\\frac{1}{k-2}-\\frac{k+1}{2}}}\\ll_k R(k,n) \\ll_k \\frac{n^{k-1}}{(\\log n)^{k-2}}.\\]The lower bound was proved by Bohman and Keevash \\cite{BoKe10}. The upper bound was proved by Ajtai, Koml\\'{o}s, and Szemer\\'{e}di \\cite{AKS80}. Li, Rousseau, and Zang \\cite{LRZ01} have shown that $\\ll_k$ in the upper bound can be improved to $\\leq (1+o(1))$. and Zang, Wenan, Asymptotic upper bounds for {R}amsey functions. Prize: no. OEIS: A000791, A059442. Tags: graph theory, ramsey theory.","id":"vf_cfd9a01e2d6e7b1e","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/986.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_3eed65065981d7f6","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:986","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_3eed65065981d7f6","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_cfd9a01e2d6e7b1e","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted f